Yes. The mascot is moving because its current CSS uses viewport-based values such as `vw`, negative `bottom`, and `clamp(...)`. When the viewport changes, those values change too, so the mascot shifts relative to the green panel.

The stable approach is:

* Keep the pattern attached to `.right-illustration`
* Anchor the mascot to the bottom of that same container
* Size the mascot relative to the panel, not the viewport
* Change the layout only at a breakpoint

Use this structure:

```html
<section class="right-illustration">
    <img class="background-pattern"
         th:src="@{/images/pattern-green.png}"
         alt="">

    <img class="mascot"
         th:src="@{/images/sales-point-hero.png}"
         alt="Mascot">
</section>
```

Then replace the current illustration styles with these.

```css
.right-illustration {
    position: relative;
    width: 100%;
    min-height: calc(100vh - 96px);
    overflow: hidden;

    border-top-left-radius: 40px;
    background-color: var(--color-green-dark);
}

.background-pattern {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;

    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;

    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center;
    z-index: 1;
}

.mascot {
    position: absolute;

    width: min(82%, 680px);
    height: auto;
    max-width: none;

    left: 50%;
    bottom: -8%;

    transform: translateX(-50%) scaleX(-1);
    transform-origin: bottom center;

    z-index: 2;
}
```

This keeps the mascot centered inside the green panel regardless of screen width.

Your current rules probably look similar to:

```css
width: clamp(420px, 46vw, 590px);
right: clamp(-40px, 4vw, 60px);
bottom: clamp(-180px, -12vw, -80px);
```

Remove those. Mixing `right`, `vw`, and negative `bottom` is what causes the movement.

## Make the green panel stable too

Use a grid where the right panel has a controlled width:

```css
.content-container {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr) minmax(430px, 42vw);
    min-height: calc(100vh - 96px);
    align-items: stretch;
}
```

For wider desktop screens, you can slightly limit it:

```css
@media (min-width: 1440px) {
    .content-container {
        grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr) minmax(520px, 40vw);
    }

    .mascot {
        width: min(78%, 720px);
        bottom: -7%;
    }
}
```

## Tablet

On smaller desktop/tablet screens, reduce the mascot proportion instead of moving it using `right`:

```css
@media (max-width: 1024px) {
    .content-container {
        grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr) minmax(340px, 40vw);
    }

    .mascot {
        width: 88%;
        bottom: -5%;
    }
}
```

## Mobile

On mobile, stack the image below the content and give the panel a fixed responsive height:

```css
@media (max-width: 768px) {
    .content-container {
        display: flex;
        flex-direction: column;
        min-height: auto;
    }

    .left-content {
        order: 1;
    }

    .right-illustration {
        order: 2;

        width: 100%;
        min-height: 420px;
        height: 55vh;
        max-height: 540px;

        border-top-left-radius: 32px;
        border-top-right-radius: 32px;
    }

    .background-pattern {
        object-position: center;
    }

    .mascot {
        width: min(78%, 430px);
        left: 50%;
        bottom: -8%;

        transform: translateX(-50%) scaleX(-1);
    }
}
```

## To match your two screenshots more closely

Your first screenshot shows the mascot too low and partially cut off. Your second shows it shifted more centrally. Start with:

```css
.mascot {
    width: min(82%, 680px);
    left: 50%;
    bottom: -6%;
    transform: translateX(-50%) scaleX(-1);
}
```

Then adjust only these two values:

```css
width: 82%;
bottom: -6%;
```

Do not change `left`, `right`, or use viewport units. This keeps the relationship between the mascot and background panel stable.
